The '''western fieldwren''' ('''''Calamanthus montanellus''''') is a species of [[bird]] in the family [[Acanthizidae]], [[Endemism|endemic]] to southwestern [[Australia]]. It is often considered a subspecies (''Calamanthus campestris montanellus'') of the [[rufous fieldwren]] (''C. campestris''), most notably by Christidis and Boles in their 2008 work, but as a separate species by many other authorities including the [[International Ornithological Committee]].<ref>Gill, F. and D. Donsker, eds. (2020). IOC World Bird List (v 10.1). Doi 10.14344/IOC.ML.10.1.  http://www.worldbirdnames.org/</ref>

A 2020 genetic and morphological analysis of the genus suggests that ''C. montanellus'' is a synonym of ''C. campestris'', and that rather than consisting of seven subspecies, ''C. campestris'' comprises two mainland subspecies ''C. c. campestris'' and ''C. c. rubiginosus'' east and west, respectively, of 133 degrees longitude, and only one island subspecies, ''C. c. hartogi''.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Burbidge |first1=Allan H. |last2=Dolman |first2=Gaynor |last3=Ottewell |first3=Kym |last4=Johnstone |first4=Ronald |last5=Burbidge |first5=Michael |date=2021-04-03 |title=Genetic and morphological relationships of fieldwrens ( Calamanthus ): implications for conservation status and management |url=https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/01584197.2021.1922293 |journal=Emu - Austral Ornithology |language=en |volume=121 |issue=1–2 |pages=75–89 |doi=10.1080/01584197.2021.1922293 |bibcode=2021EmuAO.121...75B |issn=0158-4197|url-access=subscription }}</ref>

